                      Practical 2
🚀 What is Application Load Balancer (ALB)?

👉 Application Load Balancer (ALB) is a Layer 7 (HTTP/HTTPS) load balancer in AWS.

It:

Distributes incoming traffic across multiple EC2 instances
Works based on HTTP rules (path, host, headers)
Provides high availability & fault tolerance
🔷 Real-Time Flow (Your Project)
User (Browser)
      ↓
Application Load Balancer (ALB)
      ↓
Target Group
      ↓
EC2 Instance 1 (GREEN)
EC2 Instance 2 (BLUE)

👉 ALB decides which server to send request to

⚙️ ALB Components in Terraform

Now let’s break your Terraform code into 4 main parts 👇

🔹 1. Load Balancer
resource "aws_lb" "alb" {
  name               = "suresh-alb"
  load_balancer_type = "application"
  internal           = false

  security_groups = [aws_security_group.alb_sg.id]
  subnets         = [aws_subnet.public1.id, aws_subnet.public2.id]
}
💡 Explanation:
load_balancer_type = "application" → ALB (Layer 7)
internal = false → Public (internet-facing)
subnets → Must be in at least 2 AZs (high availability)
security_groups → Allows HTTP traffic

👉 This creates the entry point for users

🔹 2. Target Group
resource "aws_lb_target_group" "tg" {
  name     = "suresh-tg"
  port     = 80
  protocol = "HTTP"
  vpc_id   = aws_vpc.main.id
}
💡 Explanation:
Group of backend servers (EC2)
ALB sends traffic to this group
Health checks happen here (by default)

👉 Think: ALB → Target Group → EC2

🔹 3. Target Group Attachment
resource "aws_lb_target_group_attachment" "t1" {
  target_group_arn = aws_lb_target_group.tg.arn
  target_id        = aws_instance.web1.id
  port             = 80
}
💡 Explanation:
Registers EC2 instances to target group
You attached:
EC2 GREEN
EC2 BLUE

👉 Now ALB knows where to send traffic

🔹 4. Listener
resource "aws_lb_listener" "listener" {
  load_balancer_arn = aws_lb.alb.arn
  port              = 80
  protocol          = "HTTP"

  default_action {
    type = "forward"
    target_group_arn = aws_lb_target_group.tg.arn
  }
}
💡 Explanation:
Listener = entry rule
Listens on port 80
Forwards traffic to target group

👉 Without listener → ALB won’t work

🔥 How Traffic Works (Step-by-Step)

User hits:

http://ALB-DNS
ALB receives request
Listener checks rules
Sends request to Target Group
Target Group selects EC2
Response comes back
🎯 Load Balancing Behavior

👉 ALB uses Round Robin by default

So:

Request 1 → GREEN
Request 2 → BLUE
Request 3 → GREEN
🔒 Security Flow
ALB Security Group → allows HTTP (80)
EC2 Security Group → allows traffic from ALB

👉 Best practice:
Instead of 0.0.0.0/0, allow only ALB SG (advanced level)
